  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 17.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And it came to pass, when they had brought them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Lot and his family) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "forth abroad",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "without",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; sc. the city), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "that he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - one of the angels (Rabbi Solomon, Jarchi, Rosenmüller, Lange, 'Speaker's Commentary'); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "the one that had taken Lot's hand",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Inglis); Jehovah speaking through the angel (Delitzsch); the angel speaking in the name of God (Keil, Kalisch); Jehovah himself, who, though not mentioned, had now appeared upon the scene (Ainsworth, Candlish) - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "said, Escape for thy life",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "for thy soul",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and clearly in this case the loss of the soul in the higher sense must have been involved in the destruction of the life); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "look not behind thee",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". From the event it may be inferred that this injunction was also given to Lot's wife and daughters; perhaps to hide God's working in the fiery judgment from mortal vision (Knobel), but more likely to express detestation of the abhorred city (Bush), to guard against the incipience of any desire to return (Lange), and to stimulate their zeal to escape destruction. Neither stay thou in all the plain - or \"circle\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "vide",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 13:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Once so attractive for its beauty, it must now be abandoned for its danger. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Escape to the mountain",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (the mountain of Moab, on the east of the Dead Sea), ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "lest thou be consumed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Genesis 19:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "When they left him here (הנּיח, to let loose, and leave, to leave to one's self), the Lord commanded him, for the sake of his life, not to look behind him, and not to stand still in all the plain (כּכּר, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 13:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but to flee to the mountains (afterwards called the mountains of Moab). In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " we are struck by the change from the plural to the singular: \"when they brought them forth, he said.\" To think of one of the two angels - the one, for example, who led the conversation - seems out of place, not only because Lot addressed him by the name of God, \"Adonai\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but also because the speaker attributed to himself the judgment upon the cities (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which is described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " as executed by Jehovah. Yet there is nothing to indicate that Jehovah suddenly joined the angels. The only supposition that remains, therefore, is that Lot recognised in the two angels a manifestation of God, and so addressed them (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 19:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as Adonai (my Lord), and that the angel who spoke addressed him as the messenger of Jehovah in the name of God, without its following from this, that Jehovah was present in the two angels. Lot, instead of cheerfully obeying the commandment of the Lord, appealed to the great mercy shown to him in the preservation of his life, and to the impossibility of his escaping to the mountains, without the evil overtaking him, and entreated therefore that he might be allowed to take refuge in the small and neighbouring city, i.e., in Bela, which received the name of Zoar (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 14:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") on account of Lot's calling it little. Zoar, the Σηγώρ of the lxx, and Segor of the crusaders, is hardly to be sought for on the peninsula which projects a long way into the southern half of the Dead Sea, in the Ghor of el Mezraa, as Irby and Robinson (Pal. iii. p. 481) suppose; it is much more probably to be found on the south-eastern point of the Dead Sea, in the Ghor of el Szaphia, at the opening of the Wady el Ahsa (vid., v. Raumer, Pal. p. 273, Anm. 14). ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]